(194, 'Apiaceae', NULL, 'Astrantia', NULL, NULL, 'major', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Claret', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'perennial', 'deciduous', 'spreading', 'part sun to part shade, avoid hot afternoon sun', 'Moist, regular water needed if in full sun', 'fertile, humus-rich, well-drained soil', 'Yes', 'summer', 'Yes', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1.3', '1.8', '1.5', '2', '4', '8', 'Claret'' is a clump-forming, herbaceous perennial, with bright green leaves cut into three to seven, toothed lobes. Its small flowers are deep red, as is its encircling ruff of bracts. ''Claret'' grows about 22 inches high and 15 inches wide. ', 'Masterwort thrives in rich well drained soil, but will tolerate a wide range of soil types including sand and clay. Plant this perennial in full sun to light or open shade and provide regular watering during dry weather. Although it will tolerate dappled shade the flowering will be sparse.  Once the first flush of flowers has finished either enjoy the dry seed heads or cut it to the ground to minimize seedlings and to enjoy a second flush of late season bloom.  ', 'This selection of masterwort was chosen for its deep wine red blooms and dark maroon-black flower stems. The richly colored blossoms are held well above the foliage for an excellent show in late spring and summer. It is easy to grow and stands out in the garden. This was one of the best masterwort performers in the GPP trials. Seedling produced from this selection will almost always come true with dark red flowers and deep black stems. ', 'Contrast ''Claret'' with bold foliage plants such as Acanthus and hostas - those with blue leaves such as ''June'' would be particularly complementary - or paler, finely cut leaves, such maidenhair fern. Use astrantias in large numbers under trees as a groundcover, and you won''t mind cutting them for fresh or dried arrangements.', NULL, NULL, 'Elliott, LaVilla, O''Byrne', '2001', 'Perennials - Bulbs', NULL, NULL, 'Plant Finder 2006-2007', 'GPP', NULL, 'Astrantia collection', '2007', NULL, '''Claret'' first arose as a seedling of ''Ruby Wedding''. ', 'Yes', NULL),
(195, 'Apiaceae', NULL, 'Astrantia', NULL, NULL, 'major', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Roma', NULL, NULL, NULL, '11,470', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'perennial', 'deciduous', 'spreading', 'part sun to part shade, avoid hot afternoon sun', 'Moist, regular water needed if in full sun', 'fertile, humus-rich, well-drained soil', 'Yes', 'summer', 'Yes', NULL, 'summer flowers', NULL, '2', '3', '2', '3', '4', '8', 'Roma'' is a clump-forming, herbaceous perennial, with bright green leaves cut into three to seven, toothed lobes. Its small flowers, produces from June to September, are soft pink, as is its encircling ruff of bracts. ''Roma'' grows about 36 inches high and 24 inches wide. ', 'Masterwort thrives in rich well drained soil, but will tolerate a wide range of soil types including sand and clay. Plant this perennial in full sun to light or open shade and provide regular watering during dry weather. Although it will tolerate dappled shade the flowering will be sparse.  Once the first flush of flowers has finished either enjoy the dry seed heads or cut it to the ground to minimize seedlings and to enjoy a second flush of late season bloom.  ', 'This heavily flowering selection has silvery-pink papery bracts surrounding a soft rose-pink center. The low bright green foliage provides a perfect foil in the garden for the profuse flowers. The bright color stands out in the landscape from late spring through the summer. This was one of the best masterwort performers in the GPP trials.   ', 'Combine ''Roma'' with bold foliage plants such as Acanthus and hostas. Its soft flower color works well with other pastels, or green-and-white variegated plants, such as Brunnera macrophylla ''Jack Frost''.', NULL, NULL, 'Elliott, LaVilla, O''Byrne', '2001', 'Perennials - Bulbs', NULL, NULL, 'Plant Finder 2006-2007', 'GPP', NULL, 'Astrantia collection', '2007', NULL, '''Roma'' is the product of a planned breeding program in the Netherlands in 1992 between Astrantia major ''Ruby Wedding'' (pollen parent) and an unnamed selection of Astrantia major var. involucrata (seed parent). U. S. Plant Patent PP11,470 was issued on August 1, 2000.', 'Yes', NULL),
(196, NULL, NULL, 'Astrantia', NULL, NULL, 'major', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Rosea', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Elliott, LaVilla, O''Byrne', '2001', 'perennials - bulbs', '', '', '', 'Eliminated', '', 'evaluation complete', '', '', '', 'No', ''),
(197, 'Apiaceae', NULL, 'Astrantia', NULL, NULL, 'major', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Rubra', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'perennial', 'deciduous', 'spreading', 'part sun to part shade, avoid hot afternoon sun', 'Moist, regular water needed if in full sun', 'fertile, humus-rich, well-drained soil', 'Yes', 'summer', 'Yes', NULL, 'summer to fall flowers', NULL, '1.3', '2.3', '1.3', '2.3', '4', '8', 'Rubra'' is a clump-forming, herbaceous perennial, with bright green leaves cut into three to seven, toothed lobes. Its small flowers are maroon, as is its encircling ruff of bracts. ''Rubra'' grows about 28 inches high and 15 inches wide. ', 'Masterwort thrives in rich well drained soil, but will tolerate a wide range of soil types including sand and clay. Plant this perennial in full sun to light or open shade and provide regular watering during dry weather. Although it will tolerate dappled shade the flowering will be sparse.  Once the first flush of flowers has finished either enjoy the dry seed heads or cut it to the ground to minimize seedlings and to enjoy a second flush of late season bloom.  ', 'This time tested cultivar of masterwort has a compact habit and flowers that almost glow in the garden. Each bloom consists of a ruff of papery bracts that are a rich maroon red that fades to silver-white in the center where tiny dark burgundy flowers perch like a pin cushion. The light colored centers give a lovely luminescent quality to the blooms. This was one of the best performers in the GPP trials. An added plus is that seedling produced will almost always come true with rich maroon flowers with a pale center.  ', 'Combine ''Rubra'' with bold foliage plants such as Acanthus and hostas. Its soft flower color works well with other pastels, or green-and-white variegated plants, such as Brunnera macrophylla ''Jack Frost''.', NULL, NULL, 'Elliott, LaVilla, O''Byrne', '2001', 'Perennials - Bulbs', NULL, NULL, 'Plant Finder 2006-2007', 'GPP', NULL, 'Astrantia collection', '2007', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL);
