(408, 'Cornaceae', 'Dogwood Family', 'Cornus', NULL, NULL, 'alba', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Elegantissima', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2 to 8', 'shrub', 'deciduous', 'spreading', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'autumn color', NULL, '10', '10', '10', '10', '2', '8', 'Variegated redtwig dogwood is a deciduous shrub that can eventually get to 10 feet high and wide, but it can easily kept smaller with pruning. It gradually spreads from the base, sending out upright shoots with red twigs. ', 'Variegated redtwig dogwood is extremely adaptable, growing in a wide range of soil types from well-drained to wet locations and from clay to sand. It is vigorous in full sun to dappled shade, but a sunnier location will provide brighter stems in winter. To encourage bright red stems cut back a third of the oldest stems to about 6 inches tall every year, leaving the strong upright young whips. ', 'Variegated redtwig dogwood is a work-horse shrub, giving a great deal for the little it asks in the way of care and attention. In the spring, bright gray-green leaves emerge with a wide, irregular margin of pure white. This variegation remains vibrant and does not fade during summer. In autumn the display changes to gold, apricot and rose-red. Once the leaves have dropped in late fall, its vibrant red stems are revealed, adding interest to the winter scene.', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Hinkley, O''Byrne, Steffen', '2001', 'Shrubs - Vines', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', NULL, NULL, '2005', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(409, NULL, NULL, 'Cornus', NULL, NULL, 'alba', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Kesselringii', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2 to 8', 'shrub', 'deciduous', 'spreading', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'autumn color', NULL, '10', '10', '10', '10', '2', '8', 'Redtwig dogwood is a deciduous shrub that can eventually get to 10 feet high and wide, but it can easily kept smaller with pruning. It gradually spreads from the base, sending out upright shoots with purple-red twigs. ', 'Black-twig dogwood is extremely adaptable, growing in a wide range of soil types from well-drained to wet locations and from clay to sand. It is vigorous in full sun to dappled shade, but a sunnier location will provide brighter stems in winter. To encourage the darkest black stems cut back a third of the oldest stems to about 6 inches tall every year, leaving the strong upright young whips. ', 'This cultivar of redtwig dogwood is grown for its unique shiny deep purple-black stems. The new spring foliage emerges flushed in inky purple and retains a hint of that dark coloring through the growing season. In autumn its leaves turn gold, apricot and rose-red. This shrub gives a great deal for the little it asks in the way of care and attention. It tolerates damp or dry soils, as well as that difficult combination of winter-wet-summer-dry locations.', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Rutherford', '2003', 'Shrubs - Vines', NULL, NULL, 'Plant Finder 2006-2007', 'GPP', NULL, 'fact sheet only', '2007', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(410, NULL, NULL, 'Cornus', NULL, NULL, 'alternifolia', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Argentea', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'tree', 'deciduous', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '20', '4', '9', 'Cornus alternifolia ''Argentea'' will reach 15 to 20 feet high in time with a greater spread.', 'Plant this small tree in a moist to well-drained soil with light or open shade.  It can be adaptable to sandy soils and clay with regular watering during dry weather. As it is noted for its beautifully layered, low branches, it should be planted where it has plenty of room to spread. The lovely layered form can easily be ruined by pruning. Consult an experienced pruner or take local classes before attempting to prune.', 'Cornus alternifolia ‘Argentea’ brings an outstanding structural element to a garden with its tiered form and bright variegation. The superlative white-edged, green leaves glow in the landscape and would be a stunning addition to the garden. It offers a distinctive branching pattern, and white flowers in late spring but it rarely berries in the Pacific Northwest. Reddish-purple twigs contrast wonderfully with the foliage.', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'committee', '2004', 'Trees - Conifers', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', NULL, NULL, '2004', 'small-tree', NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(411, NULL, NULL, 'Cornus', NULL, NULL, 'alternifolia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'tree', 'deciduous', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'autumn color', NULL, '12', '15', '30', '25', '4', '9', 'Cornus alternifolia is a small, deciduous tree that grows to 15 feet high and 12 feet wide in ten years. It matures at about 25 feet high and 30 feet wide. As it is noted for its beautifully layered, low branches, it should be planted where it has plenty of room to spread.', 'Plant this small tree in a moist to well-drained soil with light or open shade.  It can be adaptable to sandy soils and clay with regular watering during dry weather. As it is noted for its beautifully layered, low branches, it should be planted where it has plenty of room to spread. The lovely layered form can easily be ruined by pruning. Consult an experienced pruner or take local classes before attempting to prune.', 'The distinctive, tiered branching habit of Cornus alternifolia will add a touch of elegance to your garden. Pagoda dogwood is a suitable tree for small- to medium-sized gardens and is more disease resistant than many other dogwoods. It has unusual, lacy white flowers, reminiscent of the blooms of Queen Anne’s lace. In late summer, bluish-black berries decorate the tree until the birds find them! Vibrant fall color begins with burgundy hues that turn bright red with yellow toward the interior of the tree. ', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Wells', '2001', 'Trees - Conifers', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', NULL, NULL, '2004', 'small-tree', NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(412, NULL, NULL, 'Cornus', NULL, NULL, 'canadensis', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'duff plant - goes where the decaying organic matter is', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Dodson', '2003', 'perennials - bulbs', '', '', '', 'Eliminated', '', 'too difficult, too slow', '', '', '', 'No', ''),
(413, NULL, NULL, 'Cornus', NULL, NULL, 'controversa', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'June Snow', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'tree', 'deciduous', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'summer', NULL, NULL, 'autumn color', NULL, '20', '15', '40', '40', '5', '8', 'The layered braches of giant dogwood create a distinctive effect. In ten years it grows to about 15 feet high and 10 to 20 feet wide. Its mature height and width, in our region, is 40 feet high and 30 feet wide. Give it plenty of room to spead, as removing or shortening branches detracts from is exquisite silhouette. ', 'Plant this striking tree in a moist to well-drained soil with full sun to light or open shade.  It can be adaptable to sandy soils and clay with regular watering during dry weather. As it is noted for its beautifully layered, low branches, it should be planted where it has plenty of room to spread. The lovely layered form can easily be ruined by pruning. Consult an experienced pruner or take local classes before attempting to prune.', 'Cornus controversa ''June Snow'' has a distinctive and strongly horizontal branching structure. The layered branches are covered with clusters of frothy 6-inch white flowers in June and blue-black fruit clusters in autumn. Fall foliage color ranges from orange to red and plum reds. In the winter the layered branches are reminiscent of a tiered layer cake. ', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Meacham', '2002', 'Trees - Conifers', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', NULL, NULL, '2003', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(414, NULL, NULL, 'Cornus', NULL, NULL, 'controversa', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Variegata', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'tree', 'deciduous', 'spreading', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '15', '15', '25', '35', '5', '8', 'Variegated giant dogwood is relatively slow growing. As its low- and wide-spreading branches are its most ornamental feature, allow plenty of room for them to spread. Ten- year-old plants are rarely over 12 to 15 feet tall with an equal spread. Mature specimens will reach 25 to 35 feet in height with slightly less in spread. ', 'Plant this striking tree in a moist to well-drained soil with light or open shade.  It can be adaptable to sandy soils and clay with regular watering during dry weather. As it is noted for its beautifully layered, low branches, it should be planted where it has plenty of room to spread. The lovely layered form can easily be ruined by pruning. Consult an experienced pruner or take local classes before attempting to prune.', 'Variegated giant dogwood (or wedding cake tree, as it is sometimes called) can be summed up in one word -spectacular! Although often awkward looking in youth, these ‘ugly ducklings’ become swans as they mature. The branches of this tree are held out in horizontal tiers with brightly variegated leaves, giving the appearance of snow-white frosting spread over the branches. In May, this dogwood produces delicate, lacy white flowers that are followed in late summer by deep black berries. The berries glisten against the variegated leaves and are a favorite of birds.', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Jones', '2006', 'Trees - Conifers', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', NULL, NULL, '2006', 'small-tree', NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(415, NULL, NULL, 'Cornus', NULL, NULL, 'kousa', 'var.', 'chinensis', NULL, 'Milky Way', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'tree', 'deciduous', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'spring', NULL, NULL, 'autumn color', NULL, '18', '18', '25', '30', '5', '8', 'Chinese dogwood''s trunks arch outward to create a vase shape, while its branches create tiers within its crown. In ten years it reaches 10 to 18 feet high and 15 to 18 feet wide. It will ultimately grow 30 feet high and 25 feet wide.', 'Plant this slow growing tree in a moist to well-drained soil with full sun to light or open shade.  It can be adaptable to sandy soils and clay with regular watering during dry weather. The lovely layered form can easily be ruined by pruning. Consult an experienced pruner or take local classes before attempting to prune.', '‘Milky Way’ was selected for is large flowers and prolific bloom. In June star-shaped flowers open lime green and quickly change to a creamy white. The flowers can be so numerous you can hardly see any green leaves! In late summer bright red strawberry-like fruits hang from the branches until autumn turns the leaves deep red and scarlet. This small to medium sized tree has a graceful and refined layered branching pattern and older trees show a flaking patchwork of gray, tan and green on the trunk. This dogwood is resistant to dogwood anthracnose, the disease that affects our native dogwood.', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Justice, Wells', '2001', 'Trees - Conifers', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', NULL, NULL, '2001', 'small-tree', NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(416, NULL, NULL, 'Cornus', NULL, NULL, 'kousa', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Miss Satomi', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'tree', 'deciduous', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '5', '8', 'Young trees are generally vase-shaped with the branches creating tiers within its crown. Mature trees form into a more rounded shape. In ten years it reaches 10 to 18 feet high and 15 to 18 feet wide. It will ultimately grow 30 feet high and 25 feet wide.', 'Plant this slow growing tree in a moist to well-drained soil with full sun to light or open shade.  It can be adaptable to sandy soils and clay with regular watering during dry weather. The lovely layered form can easily be ruined by pruning. Consult an experienced pruner or take local classes before attempting to prune.', 'This disease resistant selection of pink flowering dogwood is a great replacement for more problem-prone cultivars. In June white flushed pink buds open and quickly become a rich rose-pink. The bright color stands out against the clean green leaves and will last longer than earlier flowering dogwood blooms. This beautiful small to medium sized tree develops a graceful layered branching pattern that shows the flowers off well. In late summer strawberry-like fruits hang from the branches followed by handsome red and orange fall color. ', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Committee', '2011', 'Trees - Conifers', NULL, NULL, 'Plant Finder 2009-2010', 'GPP', NULL, 'add Cornus ''Hearthrob'' as an option on the fact sheet', '2011', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
