(84, 'Acoraceae', 'Sweetflag', 'Acorus', NULL, NULL, 'gramineus', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ogon', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'grass', 'evergreen', 'spreading', 'full sun or light to open shade', 'frequent watering', NULL, NULL, 'summer', NULL, 'yes', NULL, NULL, '1', '1', '1', '1', '6', '10', 'This Sweetflag spreads via underground rhizomes, making it an ideal ground cover. ''Ogon'' will grow approximately one foot high. ', 'This adaptable and easy to grow groundcover succeeds well in open shade to full sun, although the golden leaf color is more intense with more light. ‘Ogon’ will grow in a wide variety of soil conditions from wet clay to rich well-drained garden soil. It prefers regular watering during dry weather and grows lush when grown in a moist location. Prune the evergreen foliage to the ground in late winter to tidy the plant if necessary. ', 'The striking chartreuse striped grass-like foliage of sweetflag makes it easy to use in the garden. It is versatile and can be used as an accent in the mixed border, as a container plant, or at the water’s edge.  The soft evergreen foliage gracefully arches to make low layered attractive mounds. ', 'The foliage combines dramatically with larger leaved plants like hostas, or for dramatic color contrast, use it under Cimicifuga simplex v. simplex ''Brunette''. For another striking combination, plant it with the black leaves of Ophiopogon planiscapus ''Nigrescens''.', NULL, NULL, 'Steffen', '2002', 'Perennials - Bulbs', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', NULL, NULL, '2002', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(85, 'Ranunculaceae', 'Buttercup', 'Actaea', NULL, NULL, 'pachypoda', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'perennial', 'deciduous', 'upright', 'open to dappled shade', 'regular watering', NULL, 'Yes', 'spring', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'spring flowers, summer berries persist until frost', NULL, '1.5', '3', '2', '3', '4', '9', 'Actaea pachypoda can reach up to 3 feet tall and 18 to 24 inches wide.', 'Plant this robust perennial in open to dappled shade with well-drained soil and regular watering during dry weather.  It is tolerant of sandy soils and clay conditions. There are no notable pest or disease problems, and it is resistant to slugs. Cut to the ground in fall once the foliage has started to yellow. ', 'Actaea pachypoda is an easy to grow woodland perennial. Planted for the dramatic cluster of white berries that develop in mid summer, each berry is dotted with a black spot giving it the common name of doll’s eyes. The bright white berries are held up on a brilliant red stalks high above the foliage.  The overall effect is unusual and eye-catching—especially in the shady woodland. The berries are poisonous, however, and should not be planted where the fruit might tempt children.', 'Actaea pachypoda combines well with ferns, bleeding hearts, and low-growing groundcovers. ', NULL, NULL, 'McLauchlan, Graves', '2004', 'Perennials - Bulbs', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', 'no', NULL, '2004', NULL, 'Native to the eastern United States & Canada. Pachypoda means "thick foot" referring to the stem that carries the berry/fruits.', 'Yes', NULL),
(86, 'Ranunculaceae', 'Buttercup', 'Actaea', NULL, NULL, 'racemosa', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'perennial', 'deciduous', 'upright', 'light to open shade', 'regular watering', NULL, 'Yes', 'summer', 'Yes', 'Flowers', NULL, NULL, '2.5', '6', '2.5', '6', '4', '8', 'Actaea racemosa is a clumping, deciduous perennial that rises 4 to 6 feet with a spread of 24 to 30 inches. It has tall tapering spikes of white flowers on wiry black-purple stems in mid-summer. ', 'Plant this robust perennial in light to open shade with well-drained soil and regular watering during dry weather.  It is tolerant of sandy soils and clay conditions. There are no notable pest or disease problems, and it is resistant to slugs. Cut to the ground in fall once the foliage has started to yellow. ', 'Actaea racemosa is an underused woodland perennial that works well in the mixed border. Tolerant of sun or shade this herbaceous bugbane forms a nice clump of upright stems that rise to 4 to 6 feet with a skirt of lacey mid-green foliage at the base with tall flower spikes of fragrant white flowers on a spike. These flower spikes can be more than 12 inches long. ', 'Actaea racemosa looks good growing with ferns, Beesia, hostas and Hakonechloa.', NULL, NULL, 'Committee', '2011', 'Perennials - Bulbs', NULL, NULL, 'Plant Finder 2009-2010', 'GPP', NULL, 'Mar 09 picked for 2011', '2011', NULL, 'Native to the eastern United States and Canada.', 'Yes', NULL),
(87, 'Ranunculaceae', 'Buttercup', 'Actaea', NULL, NULL, 'simplex', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Black Negligee', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Atropurpurea', NULL, NULL, 'perennial', NULL, 'upright', 'full sun or light shade', 'regular watering', NULL, 'Yes', 'summer', 'Yes', 'Yes', NULL, NULL, '1.5', '6', '2', '6', '3', '9', '"Actaea simplex ''Black Negligee'' is a clumping, deciduous perennial that rises 5 to 6 feet with a spread of 24 to 30 inches. It gets a tall spike of small white flowers in mid-summer."', 'Plant this robust perennial in full sun to light shade for the best foliage color. Provide well-drained soil and regular watering during dry weather.  It is tolerant of sandy soils and clay conditions. There are no notable pest or disease problems, and it is resistant to slugs. Cut to the ground in fall once the foliage has started to die back. ', 'Selected for its rich dark black-purple foliage and tall fragrant flowers ‘Black Negligee’ is a dramatic addition to the garden. Although it is tolerant of shade the best and darkest color is in full sun. The sultry foliage hugs the lower part of the plant while the flowering stems rise above with white blooming spikes that reach 4 to 5 feet.', 'Actaea simplex ''Black Negligee'' looks good growing with Hydrangea ''Preziosa'', Hydrangea quercifolia ''Snow Queen'', Thalictrum ''Hewitt''s Double'' and Hakonechloa.', NULL, NULL, 'Committee', '2011', 'Perennials - Bulbs', NULL, NULL, 'Plant Finder 2009-2010', 'GPP', NULL, 'Mar 09 picked for 2011', '2011', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(88, 'Ranunculaceae', 'Buttercup', 'Actaea', NULL, NULL, 'simplex', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Brunette', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Atropurpurea', NULL, NULL, 'perennial', 'deciduous', 'upright', 'full sun or light shade', 'regular watering', NULL, 'Yes', 'summer-fall', 'Yes', 'yes', NULL, NULL, '2', '6', '2', '6', '5', '9', 'Brunette'' will grow five to six feet high and two feet wide.', 'Plant this robust perennial in full sun to light shade for the best foliage color. Provide well-drained soil and regular watering during dry weather.  It is tolerant of sandy soils and clay conditions. There are no notable pest or disease problems, and it is resistant to slugs. Cut to the ground in fall once the foliage has started to die back. ', 'New foliage emerges deep green with a dark purple blush in early spring. As the foliage matures it deepens to an inky purple with tall flower spikes topped with fragrant spires in late summer.  ''Brunette'' is a dramatic perennial for the late summer garden. Although it is tolerant of shade the best and darkest color is in full sun. ', 'Use it with Hakonechloa macra ''Aureola'' for an eye-popping combo that will stop the neighbors. ', NULL, NULL, 'O''Byrne, LaVilla', '2002', 'Perennials - Bulbs', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', NULL, NULL, '2002', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL);
