(326, NULL, NULL, 'Cephalotaxus', NULL, NULL, 'harringtonia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '6 to 9', 'conifer', 'evergreen', NULL, 'full sun or light to dappled shade', 'occasional watering', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'winter interest', NULL, '6', '6', '15', '15', '6', '9', 'The common garden clone of this plant forms a somewhat rounded shrub with widely horizontal branches. Its 10-year size is 4 to 6 feet high and the same in width. At maturity it can reach 12 to 15 feet high and wide.', 'Plum yew grows in full sun or light to dappled shade. Its best growth is in well-drained soil, but it will tolerate sand or clay. It needs occasional watering during prolonged dry weather. It will naturally grow with a graceful layered form so minimal pruning is required. ', 'The plum yew is an unusual evergreen conifer with thick dark green needles arranged in an attractive v-shaped pattern along the branch. It is prized for its graceful layered branching and its unusual texture as a large shrub to small tree. Great for the shade! ', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Hartlage, Demarsh-D.', '2002', 'Trees - Conifers', NULL, NULL, 'Dirr Jacobson Plant Finder 2004 A-Z', 'GPP', 'no', NULL, '2005', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
(327, NULL, NULL, 'Ceratostigma', NULL, NULL, 'plumbaginoides', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '6 to 9', 'perennial', 'deciduous', 'spreading', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'summer', NULL, NULL, 'autumn color ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '6', '9', 'Dwarf plumbago is a low-growing, spreading perennial. It rarely grows more than 12 to 15 inches tall and spreads 12 to 18 inches a year. It is not a dense groundcover and is at its best when mixed with other perennials or groundcovers to extent its season of interest. ', 'Place dwarf plumbago in full sun or light shade in rich, sandy well-drained soil. Occasional summer watering encourages a heavier late season bloom. Once the fall color ends it can be cut to the ground. ', 'Dwarf plumbago sparkles in late summer and autumn with sapphire-blue flowers that are increasingly silhouetted against the rich reds and oranges of its fall foliage color. Understated during early summer, it rambles and weaves through other plantings, preparing for its late season surprise. Ceratostigma plumbaginoides is late to come up in the spring. Because of this, it makes a great companion for bulbs, often not growing strongly until the bulb foliage starts to die back. It then quickly covers the spent bulbs’ leaves. ', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'C. Allen', '2006', 'Perennials - Bulbs', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GPP', NULL, NULL, '2006', NULL, NULL, 'Yes', NULL),
